Britain anticipates an imminent statement from the IRA regarding a potential abandonment of violence, signaling a new era in Northern Irish politics.
Hopes are high for a swift disarmament plan by the end of June, following the 1998 Good Friday peace deal.
Political figures stress the importance of IRA cooperation for lasting peace, with calls for an end to criminal activities.
Recent appeals for democratic engagement by Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams aim to bridge divides and move towards reconciliation.
The focus remains on concrete actions by the IRA to build trust and pave the way for a self-governing Northern Ireland.
